VHe had also specialised in the rendition ofpallaviesafter learning from Calcutta Krishnamurthy. Thus, he carried the influence of all but appears to have Seshagopalan on him more.His performance was held for South Indian Cultural Association (SICA), last week at Ravindra Bharati. Yet his erudition was visible, because of which he has already bagged some titles and awards from prestigioussabhas.R. Dinakar on violin, Jayabhasker on mridangam and D.Janardhan on ghatam accompanied him on this occasion.Kasturi Rangan opened with a traditionalVirioboniAta Tala varnam with exercisingswaras.Raghunandanain Sahana, a very pleasing rendition, was the invocation.Then, he took up delineation ofragaShanmukhapriya after settling himself well with earlier numbers. And, the rendition of thekriti,Mari Vere Dikkevarayya Ramawas quite expressive taking care of thesahityaexpression too.Thenerevalandswarakalpanawere fluent and carried the melodic line.Madhava Mamavain Neelambari, a Narayana Teertha&#8217;sTarangamwas presented later.Then, he essayedVaraliin which he rendered a Tamil composition. Kasturi Rangan&#8217;s mainragaof the evening was Mohana.He evolved it well from one octave to another with some embellishments in each.Nanu Palimpaof Thyagaraja in thisragawas an apt choice for its literary and musical appeal.Thenerevalandswaramwere impressive and imaginative. Thetani avartanampresented by the percussionist duo was spirited and added to the general appeal of the whole concert.They proved quite intuitive in their accompaniment all through.Secretary of SICA Chakrapani said that SICA was going to hold its 48th Annual music festival starting from March 10, lasting for a week, featuring top grade artistes of the South.
